==The first thing that should be done is move this board to the newest version of Millchan==
This board is running on a year old version. The newest version has many new features and bugfixes.
But the most important bugfix is that in the version this board is running ==content that is muted is still shared because of a bug==.
Since the site owner doesn't seem particularly technical, an official update does not seem to be very likely to happen in the near future. '''There probably is a way to override the official version and run the new version client-side'''
This mechanism would also allow users to patch their own software to add new features.
Some of the bug fixes and features that I can think of:
-Currently Zeronet opens too many Tor circuits, banning us from the Guard node.
-No option to disable BO blacklist by default.
-I don't liike the rotating placeholder, too distracting.
-Announce to trackers more often. When all trackers all lost re-announce takes too long.
-No way to limit number of total connections, which can overload Tor and cheap home routers.
-Of course, the anti-fingerprint features preventing posting bug with Tor Browser,  but that's already fixed in the new version of Millchan.
-No way to sage. Not sure if that's on the new Millchan version.
I'm going to begin reading the docs to see what I can dig up. Anyone who wants to help? https://zeronet.readthedocs.io/en/latest/

>>870e59c8-4214-4669-8d69-b29390f2d193
Oh, and I forgot, '''no DHT support''', which stops the sharing when we lose all the trackers, and opens us up to censorship by way of centralization.

>>d0a10661-cba4-4163-9cf8-982d6a62b4f4
>It's a -little- encrypted.
I know. But so are modern torrents, and they're still fucked with by the fucking copyright agencies sending DMCAs. Imagine how much more active the jews are in harvesting IPs from here, and recording what content they're seeding.
>A trusted VPN is therefore technically as secure as tor for zeronet traffic.
There is no trusted VPN. Tor doesn't require trusting a single entity, it benefits from probabilities by requiring **in principle, ignoring correlation attacks** that at least ONE of your relays isn't compromised.

>>a4fefda2-46c4-4d4e-8a1c-e9814f063770
>And yes, "blacklisted" users' data still stays on your hard drive and is being updated. You just don't see it.

>>d0a10661-cba4-4163-9cf8-982d6a62b4f4
>But you have to submit to the site with the same hash checked scripts since everything is private public key checked to prevent tampering. 
Wrong. If you think so, then tell me '''how''' they do it.
If your argument is there's a "here goes the hash of the script you used" field, you can just put in the hash of the official scripts while running the patched ones.
There's just no way for your peers to verify that you're using the official scripts, unless they knew the inputs **(they don't, at the very least because you're introducing your messages that there's no way they'd know unless they can read minds, but also because if they already had the data you have they wouldn't be asking you for it)** and ran the scripts over the same data themselves, but that's impossible, because the network relies in peers providing not-seen-before data. **and also this mechanism has nothing to do with public key encryption/digital signatures**

>>d0a10661-cba4-4163-9cf8-982d6a62b4f4
>Ps, i2p is not inherently better.
AFAIK, in theory i2p is better because it implements onion routing itself. In practice, I think Zeronet is better because running it over Tor (which is a better tested implementation of onion routing than i2p) makes that objection pointless, and also decoupling the onion routing and p2p layers is good because you can choose to run it over clearnet too if you wanna risk it or are anonymizing by other means.

>>d0169130-1327-425b-aae4-00211b2aec89

Yes, that's what I mean. There's no VPN I personally trust and neither should anyone else have one.
>and then maybe also connect to that through tor.
Sure, that's fine if you put it in the beginning of the chain so your ISP doesn't see you're using Tor, or if you put it at the other end of Tor to access websites that block Tor and pay for it through anonymous means (this last use is pointless for Zeronet though).

>>a82f274b-91db-4a55-b8ea-6a86403d9efd
>That being said zeronet is also a bit of a privacy leak for tor itself.
Yeah. It'd be cool if there was some way of reducing the bits of deanonymization. For instance, clients could download the data in a deterministic pattern in say 25% increments before beginning seeding that data, thus only leaking 2 bits of identifying information (in theory). And also generating a new user cert for every post, but I think the latest version of Millchan provides an option for that doesn't it.

>>cb3983f4-6ca5-4560-a884-11b39615c827
>Many clearnet sites have tor iframes so people can browse tor without installing software.
A clearnet proxy to Tor would be seen as a normal user connecting to a normal IP.
When using Tor (at least if you use it for most things you do online) the pattern of traffic is way different, it shows up as you connecting mainly to a few more or less static IPs that when reverse DNSd straight up say they're Tor guards right in the domain name. This stands out way more than some faggot accessing onion.link or whatever once in a lifetime.
>It's not as open ended
What do you mean by that.
>or as scary as you think.
I use Tor for about half of my web browser. I think it's somewhat scary. It certainly will raise a few eyebrows if an agent **or a bot** is checking up on **certainly watchlisted a lot by now** people's ISP traffic every now and then.

posts.body: Post em.

posts.subject: Let's settle this once and for all
posts.body:
Is cyberpunk merely an artistic style or is it also a way of life?
Personally I think there are two cyberpunks, and the one depicted in fiction has little to do with what I would consider 'cyberpunk' in real life. Also IMO people can't be 'cyberpunks', but some things are 'cyberpunk', like this board.

>>8a813b75-b335-43ad-8456-67d23013c424
>sort of like those html to email fetches
I didn't mean retrieving the posts from the dedicated machine (I was thinking of that just to not be a leecher), but yeah, if there could be a way of using it as a direct LAN peer without breaking anonymity it would be pretty cool.

>>40a345ab-9514-41ee-b20c-f6e251a473c2
It turned out to be just a regional issue, the video just didn't download from my geographical location (don't ask me why).

>>4d4e4300-2233-4dfe-bce9-3d4eddd3db94
But how would you know when you're going to be close to a recognition camera, though?
I mean, you could do it every time you're in a densely populated place, but that's also where you're most likely to be seen by a cop having an obscured plate. **also I wonder if that thing's illegal**

>>047d21a6-78a2-4ff2-9c68-9a7864276042
>First, user who created the board CAN NOT MODERATE IT. It is not possible.
He can blacklist people, which means you won't see the posts by default unless you click the checkmark on the bottom.
>Second, names are not unique. There can be a thousand different boards named /leftypol/.
You'd have to bypass the web frontend I guess. When you try to create one in the normal way it warns you there's already a board with the same name.
